{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The wait time between retries doubles with each consecutive failure, up to a configured maximum.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is primarily backoff math/state progression inside one component. A unit test with deterministic inputs (attempt count, base delay, max delay) can catch real failures (wrong exponent, cap off-by-one) without module wiring. Higher levels are disqualified by behavior text: no OS/network/subprocess or external model dependency is required.","test_description":"Test `computeBackoff(attempt, base, max)` (or equivalent policy object) over attempts 1..N and assert delays double then clamp at `max` exactly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.82,"Integration":0.16,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The retry logic correctly identifies a rate-limit response and computes the appropriate wait time before the next attempt.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff: HTTP response classification (e.g., 429/headers) feeding retry scheduler delay computation. A pure unit of either side can miss contract mismatches (header units, missing field handling). System is disqualified by behavior text: it does not require real network behavior, only correct interpretation of response data.","test_description":"Wire retry coordinator + response parser with stubbed responses (429 with `Retry-After`, 429 without header, non-429). Assert retry decision and computed wait match policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"After the wait, the client actually resends the original request and returns the successful result to the caller transparently.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This requires interaction between timer/backoff, request execution, and response propagation. Real failure is often in orchestration (request not resent, mutated payload, result not unwrapped). System was considered but rejected: behavior text only requires resend semantics, which in-process fake timers + stub transport can validate exactly.","test_description":"Use fake clock and stub transport returning [rate-limited, success]. Call `call()` once; advance time; assert second transport invocation reuses original request params and final resolved value equals success payload.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.82,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"After the configured maximum number of retries, the client returns a typed `QuotaExhaustedError` rather than a generic error.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Typed error emission depends on retry-loop termination plus error mapping. A single-function unit test may miss that loop exhaustion path returns wrong error type after orchestration. Higher levels are disqualified: no real OS/network requirement in behavior text; deterministic local stubs are sufficient.","test_description":"Stub transport to always return rate-limit failures; run `call()` with `maxRetries=k`; assert exactly `k+1` attempts and rejection is instance of `QuotaExhaustedError` with expected metadata.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full retry chain — initial call, backoff retries, quota tracking — terminates correctly and does not loop indefinitely before surfacing the error.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This explicitly spans multiple local modules (retry state, backoff, shared quota accounting) and targets a cross-module liveness failure (infinite loop). Integration is the minimum boundary. System was considered but rejected because behavior text does not require real subprocess/network/OS primitives; fake timers can deterministically expose non-termination bugs.","test_description":"Run end-to-end library flow with always-rate-limited stub transport and fake timers; assert promise settles within bounded simulated time, attempt count is finite, and terminal error is surfaced.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.83,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Requests issued concurrently from multiple async callers in the same process all draw from the same shared quota bucket.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure occurs at shared-state coordination boundary across concurrent callers, not in a single function. Needs multiple modules/call paths wired to one quota manager. System rejected by behavior text: it explicitly scopes to \"same process\" and can be reproduced with in-process async concurrency and stubbed transport.","test_description":"Launch N concurrent `call()` invocations against one client instance with deterministic stub responses; assert quota decrements are globally shared and aggregate sends respect single bucket limits.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When multiple requests are waiting to be sent, they are dispatched in the order they were originally submitted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is queueing/order behavior across async scheduling + dispatcher modules. Unit-testing queue internals alone can miss integration bugs where enqueue/dequeue boundaries reorder work. Higher levels are disqualified by behavior text: no real OS/network or AI output dependency is required.","test_description":"Submit several calls rapidly while quota forces waiting; use controlled cl